			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The distinction between NACL_BUILD_ARCH and NACL_TARGET_ARCH is obsolete and should be removed because it just confuses people.  (The same applies to the 'build_*' and 'target_*' flags inside the Scons build.)

The reason for having this distinction was to allow cross-building the validators, so that the ARM validator can be run on x86, for example.  However:

 * A better way to do that is to arrange for all validators to be built as part of each architecture's build: see issue 574.  To that end, we already build the ARM ncval-core as part of the x86-32 build.

 * Configurations where the build arch doesn't match the target arch are never tested, so are probably very bitrotted.
